{
  "text": "It cannot be completely ruled out that the PHAAs are the seismic response to the authigenic carbonate-cemented sediment. An example outcropping at the seabed was seen in the Gulf of Mexico [CITATION_1] . The carbonate cements could form as a result of 8 anaerobic methane oxidation that develops in the methane-rich environment [CITATION_2] . But the PHAAs, which are ~70 mbsf, may be too deep for this methane oxidation to take place as the sulfate-methane interface (SMI), which is at the base of the sulfate reduction zone, is normally at < 70 mbsf [CITATION_3] .",
